in the principles

00:41:59.510 --> 00:42:02.000
that I'm laying out here and
that I lay out in the book.

00:42:04.620 --> 00:42:06.140
Because of
postmodernism, because

00:42:06.140 --> 00:42:09.120
of a whole lot of
different things,

00:42:09.120 --> 00:42:12.560
basically, the mantra
among architects

00:42:12.560 --> 00:42:17.000
is you can't really
predict people's experience

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:18.400
of an environment.

00:42:18.400 --> 00:42:19.850
We don't know enough.

00:42:19.850 --> 00:42:21.740
It's all subjective.

00:42:21.740 --> 00:42:27.810
French people experience it
differently from Americans.

00:42:27.810 --> 00:42:29.390
No.

00:42:29.390 --> 00:42:31.370
There's a lot we know.

00:42:31.370 --> 00:42:35.510
And that knowledge should
become much more widespread,

00:42:35.510 --> 00:42:38.330
and should be
incorporated into what

00:42:38.330 --> 00:42:43.250
clients expect from the
designers that they hire.

00:42:43.250 --> 00:42:46.400
And that means
looking to fields that

00:42:46.400 --> 00:42:52.130
are not necessarily directly
connected to architecture

00:42:52.130 --> 00:42:54.517
like environmental
psychology and so on.

00:42:54.517 --> 00:42:56.600
And there are architecture
firms that are actually

00:42:56.600 --> 00:42:58.520
putting environmental
psychologists,

00:42:58.520 --> 00:43:02.900
and cognitive scientists,
and so on on staff.

00:43:02.900 --> 00:43:08.430
So get the right stuff,
that would be my advice.

