I can't remember the
details of the study,

00:45:35.252 --> 00:45:37.460
but it was something like
they did two weeks of class

00:45:37.460 --> 00:45:38.360
in that classroom.

00:45:38.360 --> 00:45:44.120
And then, they did another two
weeks in a similar classroom

00:45:44.120 --> 00:45:49.890
in terms of size and orientation
and arrangement of furniture.

00:45:49.890 --> 00:45:52.700
But the furniture was soft.

00:45:52.700 --> 00:45:54.830
And there were
rugs on the floor.

00:45:54.830 --> 00:45:56.390
And there were task lights.

00:45:56.390 --> 00:45:59.150
And there was a
couch behind them.

00:45:59.150 --> 00:46:03.200
And the students participated
something astonishingly,

00:46:03.200 --> 00:46:08.300
like 40% more and
were more engaged

00:46:08.300 --> 00:46:11.060
and therefore learn
more in what was

00:46:11.060 --> 00:46:14.510
the so-called soft classroom
than in the hard classroom.

00:46:14.510 --> 00:46:15.680
People just don't know.

00:46:15.680 --> 00:46:17.340
They don't know
these things matter.

00:46:17.340 --> 00:46:19.010
And part of the reason
that people don't really

00:46:19.010 --> 00:46:20.676
appreciate the build
environment so much

00:46:20.676 --> 00:46:24.680
is because most of our
thoughts are nonconscious

00:46:24.680 --> 00:46:29.210
and the built environment
is inert and static,

00:46:29.210 --> 00:46:31.306
and so you don't pay a
lot of attention to it,

00:46:31.306 --> 00:46:33.180
but that doesn't mean
it's not affecting you.

00:46:46.661 --> 00:46:48.160
SPEAKER 1: Have you
seen any studies

00:46:48.160 --> 00:46:51.650
that show how
people develop maybe

00:46:51.650 --> 00:46:55.610
in more of a city versus a
suburb versus the country?

00:46:55.610 --> 00:46:59.650
Or I'm sure there's no average
American city or suburb

00:46:59.650 --> 00:47:02.830
or country, so to speak,
but in the same way

00:47:02.830 --> 00:47:07.620
that you're talking about how
certain buildings are designed,

00:47:07.620 --> 00:47:10.240
have you expanded it more
on a macro level and just

00:47:10.240 --> 00:47:12.670
to kind of understand how
people develop in those three

00:47:12.670 --> 00:47:13.812
types of environments?

00:47:13.812 --> 00:47:15.270
SARAH WILLIAMS
GOLDHAGEN: Oh, sure.

00:47:15.270 --> 00:47:18.250
Absolutely.

00:47:18.250 --> 00:47:21.520
I tend to emphasize it
less because, particularly

00:47:21.520 --> 00:47:26.860
the suburb versus city, is a
pretty well-known comparison.

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:30.720
Suburbs are very isolating,
and they're very homogeneous.

00:47:30.720 --> 00:47:37.690
And cities are like
beehives of diversity.

00:47:37.690 --> 00:47:40.480
They're different people and
there's different things to do.

00:47:43.810 --> 00:47:49.240
So you tend, in a suburb, to
get a very homogenized view

00:47:49.240 --> 00:47:51.220
of your social world.

00:47:51.220 --> 00:47:54.250
And also, there are times--

00:47:54.250 --> 00:47:56.350
I wouldn't say this
to my husband--

00:47:56.350 --> 00:47:59.770
but there are times when I
think the nuclear family is

00:47:59.770 --> 00:48:03.624
about the worst thing that
modern society has given us.

00:48:03.624 --> 00:48:05.540
There are other times
when I think it's great.

00:48:05.540 --> 00:48:14.320
But kids that grow up with
more than two role models,

00:48:14.320 --> 00:48:18.160
if you hate your dad, you
like your uncle or stuff

00:48:18.160 --> 00:48:20.770
where they're just more
people around and more

00:48:20.770 --> 00:48:23.140
internet communities--

00:48:23.140 --> 00:48:25.390
we know this-- are
psychologically much

00:48:25.390 --> 00:48:27.490
healthier kids.

00:48:27.490 --> 00:48:31.330
So there's definitely a big
urban dimension to this.

00:48:31.330 --> 00:48:36.970
So much so, the configuration
of the streetscape

00:48:36.970 --> 00:48:40.670
can either encourage people
to connect with one another.

00:48:40.670 --> 00:48:42.970
To look at each other.

00:48:42.970 --> 00:48:47.440
Or to put their eyes down and
just look at the sidewalk.

00:48:47.440 --> 00:48:49.840
There's a ream of stuff
out there about this.

00:48:53.019 --> 00:48:54.560
AUDIENCE: Sarah,
thanks for the talk.

00:48:54.560 --> 00:48:55.601
