00:48:55.601 --> 00:48:58.700
I have not read your book, but
I do have a question for you.

00:48:58.700 --> 00:48:59.780
It seems as though--

00:48:59.780 --> 00:49:01.490
my understanding of
one of the hurdles

00:49:01.490 --> 00:49:03.610
to getting great
design more ubiquitous,

00:49:03.610 --> 00:49:05.570
whether it's in the
United States or globally,

00:49:05.570 --> 00:49:09.950
is this understanding
of the value gap.

00:49:09.950 --> 00:49:11.540
And I think the way
I would describe

00:49:11.540 --> 00:49:15.140
it is that the economic
costs are easily understood,

00:49:15.140 --> 00:49:17.000
and they're written
in economic terms,

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:20.060
and they're easy to
measure, essentially.

00:49:20.060 --> 00:49:22.100
And then the value
component to great design

00:49:22.100 --> 00:49:25.040
is often talked about in
terms of enrichment and things

00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:27.200
that are not
economically defined.

00:49:27.200 --> 00:49:30.280
Do you have any
examples, whether be they

00:49:30.280 --> 00:49:33.980
public or private
projects, where

00:49:33.980 --> 00:49:36.740
folks have done a really
good job of economically

00:49:36.740 --> 00:49:39.306
defining the value proposition
of doing greater design?

00:49:39.306 --> 00:49:41.055
SARAH WILLIAMS GOLDHAGEN:
Absolutely, yes.

00:49:43.700 --> 00:49:47.210
Post-occupancy evaluation
is what it's called,

00:49:47.210 --> 00:49:50.030
and it's something that
architects are still

00:49:50.030 --> 00:49:52.520
having trouble with
because it kind of holds

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:54.020
them accountable
in ways they wish

00:49:54.020 --> 00:49:56.510
they weren't held accountable.

00:49:56.510 --> 00:49:59.270
But there are
post-occupancy evaluations.

00:49:59.270 --> 00:50:00.860
I can think of two.

00:50:00.860 --> 00:50:06.260
One is a retail
supermarket in which

00:50:06.260 --> 00:50:12.410
they were in a big boxy type
space, no natural light.

00:50:12.410 --> 00:50:14.420
And then they moved into
a different building

00:50:14.420 --> 00:50:26.450
that had skylights, and 25%
to 35% more customers, a lot.

00:50:26.450 --> 00:50:32.030
A lot of studies have been
done on workplace productivity,

00:50:32.030 --> 00:50:34.790
including by people who had been
working on this for a long time

00:50:34.790 --> 00:50:37.010
and really know what they're
doing so the studies are

00:50:37.010 --> 00:50:42.650
excellent, in which
they show that employee

00:50:42.650 --> 00:50:45.079
retention, workplace
productivity, all these things

00:50:45.079 --> 00:50:45.870
have been measured.

00:50:45.870 --> 00:50:52.910
They go up dramatically in
better designed environments.

00:50:52.910 --> 00:50:54.660
So those are two
examples I can think of.

00:50:54.660 --> 00:50:56.030
There are others, too.

00:50:56.030 --> 00:50:58.732
There was-- actually,
it was in Michigan.

00:50:58.732 --> 00:51:04.460
It was a factory in Michigan
that they hired an architect

00:51:04.460 --> 00:51:06.860
who does a lot of green stuff.

00:51:06.860 --> 00:51:10.340
And he did a little bit like
that emergency department.

00:51:10.340 --> 00:51:12.860
He put these little
green moments

00:51:12.860 --> 00:51:14.720
all through the building.

00:51:14.720 --> 00:51:17.120
And, again,
productivity went up.

00:51:17.120 --> 00:51:18.380
People were happier.

00:51:18.380 --> 00:51:20.780
They stayed at the jobs
longer, et cetera, et cetera.

00:51:20.780 --> 00:51:23.750
So there are coming to be
more and more examples,

00:51:23.750 --> 00:51:28.340
and we need lot more
studies of that.

